I wanted a CAD model of the switch for a project but the model also prints well enough for a tangible application. The model includes some tiny stubs beneath the leaf spring to help the material bridge which are easily snipped off after printing. To get a CAD model without the stubs, change the "support=true" parameter in the limswitch() call near the bottom of the file to "support=false".

Introducing 3DPWPE - a 3D Printed Windmill Producing Electricity

Introduction:

Here you can find the printed parts to build a very simple and easy wind mill. This windmill produces electricity and is capable to output about 1W, 5V (enough to charge a mobile phone!).

Why is this project cool/something special?

You may ask yourself: Why is this project so cool? There are many answers. One answer is that this project is pretty useful, you could charge for example a battery pack, your phone or just show of your awesome 3D printing skills. :) Another point is the simplicity of this project. It doesn't use an expensive Nema Stepper or has complicated gear ratios. It uses a cheap standard electric motor and a rubber band as a transistion. This makes it a very cheap weekend project (<5$).

Design goals:

This project was designed using Solidworks. I always kept the simplicity in mind so that 3D printing beginners can also build it. One design goal was the easy printability. The parts don't need support at all and can be printed on a standard Makerbot Replicator 5th Gen. Another goal was to ban all the complicated and expensive parts (Stepper Motor, gear transition). I also focused on the looks of the windmill. You wanna put it in your garden so it should look cool right?! :)

How it works:

The wind blows on the blades of the windmill. Because the blades are angled (35° works good) the blades "want to escape". They can only "escape" by turning around the axis, so they turn around. This rotation is pretty slow. Because of this there is a bigger pulley and a smaller pulley. The bigger pully is fastened on the rotor axis, the smaller one on the generator axis. Between the pulleys runs a rubber band. The rubber band and the pulleys create the transition, so the generator turns faster than the rotor. The generator now transforms the rotation energy into electricity. You can use the electricity for every purpose you want.

How much does this project cost to make?

I thought a lot and came to the conclusion that I wanted to keep the cost as low as possible. Therefore I didn't use an expensive Stepper Motor as a generator. Because of this you need under 5$ to make this project!

23 of June 2015
  • added the basic files of the frame
25 of June 2015
  • added pictures of the CAD assembly
  • added a Solidworks assembly file
  • added the rest of the files, construction work of prototype "3DPWPE V1" is done

Any questions?

Simply drop a comment or write me a message, if you have questions! Always happy to help! :)

You will need:

Printed parts:
  • cover.STL x2 (optional)
  • gear1.STL x1
  • sidepart1.STL x1
  • sidepart2.STL x1
  • topbottomx2.STL x2
  • axisstop.STL x2
  • rotor.STL x1
  • rotorspacer.STL x1
  • propellor.STL x4
Non printed parts:
  • 180mm 2.9mm rod
  • a 23.3mm diameter electric motor
  • some M3 20 screws
  • wires
  • an electronic circuit of your choice (what will you power with the electricity generated :)!?)

Suggested print settings:

  • Extrusion widh: 0.48mm
  • Layer height: 0.2mm
  • Infill percentage: 30-40% (the higher, the better)
  • Print speed: 30-100mm/s (depending on your printer)
  • Support: off

Assembly instructions:

Before you start:

If you don't know how to execute a step look at the pictures of the assembly. They will help you!

Printing the parts/cleaning the parts:

Print the parts. You can use the settings recommended below. You should drill out the hole on the sidepart1.STL and sidepart2.STL with a 4mm drill to smooth the surface, so there will be very little friction.

Pressfitting the pulley:

Take your gear1.STL and one axisstop.STL and press fit them on the rod. Move them to the middle of the rod.

Pressfitting the generator:

Get your generator-motor and the sidepart1.STL and press the generator in the hole it is supposed to go in. Don't hesitate to use some force.

Assembling the outer case:

Get your rubber band and lay it over the gear1.STL. Then take both sides and put those sides over the axis so that the gear1.STL and the axisstop.STL is between them. Use the top parts and 4 M3 screws to fasten the sides together.

Finishing the trasition:

Take the end of the rubber band and put it over both pulleys.

Pressfitting the rotor:

This part is very tricky. Be very careful and have patience. Use a hammer to carefully tab the end of the axis first trough rotorspacer.STL then in rotor.STL. You can now use the second axisstop.STL to cover up the other end of the axis.

Final assembly:

Move everything on the axis like shown in the pictures in the gallery. Use a drop of super glue to hold everything nice and firm on the rod. You can also now put the four propellor.STL in the rotor.STL and align them (35° works very good). If you want to, you can use the cover.STL to cover up the big gaps, just remove the 4 M3 screws and put the cover.STL between the screws and the assembly.

What will you power?

You can now power your circuit with your fancy new windmill or can directly solder it to some LEDs or other interesting stuff.

Enjoy!

Designed by our teacher to get her monitor to the correct height for ergonomic purposes.

For design specs check out this PDF: http://www.thingiverse.com/download:1415140

Discovery - The design looks cool but is a bit flawed. There is a lot of torque at the pivot joints when the stand is not completely vertically extended. This means there is definitely a weight limit. It is currently being used to hold a smallish LCD monitor and had to be tightened with wrenches because hand tightening wasn't enough.

Design suggestions: Modifying the arms and connection points to have a "toothed" pattern so that the rotation would lock in place OR a scissor lift design which would probably be able to hold more weight and only fall in a vertical (instead of arcing) direction if it couldn't bear the weight load.

All parts printed with 6 shells and 25% infill for strength.

1x Platform (to hold small monitor or other light object)

7x Hex Bolt Grips
4x Clamp Pads
4x Clamps (Size options - see accompanying pdf for details)
1x Arm 1 (Size options - see accompanying pdf for details)

Hardware:
7x 3/8" - 1 1/2" Hex Bolts
4x 3/8" Hex Nuts

author: garym77

description.text: TV Antennae

The area between the function y=2x^2-x^3 and the x-axis is rotated about the y-axis creating a volume of revolution. This model shows this volume approximated by 16 cylindrical shells. (The 16th shell in the center has zero volume so is not included in the print model!) Note that this volume of revolution is an example of one whose volume cannot be computed using the method of disks.

This model was designed and printed by my WLU summer research student Ryan McDonnell ('17). A detailed description of how it was designed can be found at http://mathvis.academic.wlu.edu/2015/06/24/volume-by-cylindrical-shells/

This object was made on a MakerBot2X. We recommend the following settings:
2 shells
0.20mm layer height
10% infill (hexagonal pattern)
no supports
raft on

The first time we printed this, we printed it without a raft. It was incredibly difficult to remove the object from the build bed. So we recommend printing with a raft, hopefully the object will be easier to remove.

remixed_from.title: Trapezoid Screw Thread Module: Now with a Shaft!

description.text: When I tried to make a throated worm screw ( http://www.thingiverse.com/derivative:9733 ), I ran into an issue: the thread profile was being extruded along the right curve in space, but there was no skewing of the profile to fit the curve. You can see what I mean by comparing the images for this thing to the images for its parent. The tip of the thread remains vertical, no matter how the thread tapers or widens around the shaft. In the case of a throated worm screw, this meant that the worm gear would hit the parts of the profile that had not tapered out of the way properly. Had to redo the polyhedron the whole thing rests on, and I took the opportunity to redo all the math vectorially, cuz it's cleaner that way. Also went ahead and made the shaft follow a curve defined by functions, like the thread does. More versatile, but we're not yet where the shaft could be a torus and the thread winds around it. Now that I have this working in this stand-alone script, I need to work it back into the screw library ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8793 ) and the throated worm screw will be a synch. As I've just received my Thingomatic, however, (thanks MBI!) this might take a back seat to assembly, calibration, printing, etc... Sorry!

It's a stand-alone script, it does NOT need the library. The latest code will be in the GitHub repository:
https://github.com/syvwlch/Thingiverse-Projects/tree/master/ExtrudePolygon

Modular Rostock delta push rods for a larger-than-standard Rostock build. I needed 300mm center-to-center but only had a 6" (150mm) print area to work with.

Each segment adds 100mm to the total rod length; you'll probably want to double-check the actual length, adjust, and re-tighten connecting screws for best results. I used M3x10, but M3x12 would have been better.

These could be extended to 400mm or 500mm, but mine are already a bit more flexible than I'd like and will eventually be replaced with carbon fiber tubes & Traxxas 1942 ball connectors. Nevertheless, maybe someone will find this useful.

This design is a derivative of Asger's half-rods, itself a derivative of a half-rod design by sivar2311. The 'Mid' rod should be fully compatible with either of those designs if you need to extend them to about 350mm.

Using only the 'End' parts will net you a 200mm rod; one 'mid' part will achieve 300mm, and two should end up at 400mm. These are measured center-to-center your firmware will expect (I use Marlin) for DELTA_DIAGONAL_ROD in configuration.h (or equivalent), total length will be longer.

This results in 12x 'End' rods and 6x 'Mid' rods for a 300mm delta configuration. I managed to print all 18 parts in exactly two batches on a 150mmx150mm (heated) bed with ABS at 0.3mm, but it's probably better to use 0.2mm if you can.

Rods were fastened with M3x10mm machine screws; some have washers, some don't, and I wasn't consistent between lock nuts and standard ones. So far, every combination has held up fine, but I'll (probably?) update this with better information after I've used these for a while. Note that M3x12mm would have been better, especially if using washers and/or lock nuts.

If you're building a standard Rostock without changing any dimensions, these are not going to work. The 200mm configuration might work with a 'Rostock mini' build (albeit with reduced build height), but you'll definitely need to change the rod lengths in firmware.

description.text: For weighing powders and pouring into bottles

A jig for making multiple stranded twisted wire. Works with anything up to 20awg wire (without scaling).
Holes are placed to align the wire while twisting. 5 and 6 strand twisted wire strands work better with a center.
3 stranded wire is the most stable. 5 and 6 work well with a center.
Pictured is 20awg and 28awg 3 strand twisted copper wire as well as 20awg 4, 5+c, and 6+c in the second picture.

• Print the jigs.
  • Get some wire to twist.
  • Feed the individual wire strands through the jig.
  • Use pliers to hold the strands at the top.
  • Turn the jig while holding the pliers tight.
    • Make sure the jig is as close as possible to the bottom of the twisted wire.
    • Keep moving your anchor point as the twisted wire gets longer, using cushion (ie rubber, sponge, paper) to not crush the wire.
  • Do fancy things with the twisted wire.
    • .
  • Weights can be attached to the bottom of the wire to aid in keeping the wire from counter-wrapping below the jig. This is especially important with very thin and weak wire.
  • Holes drilled in a CD can also be used to further separate the wires at the bottom (must use weights to keep wire fed through CD holes).
  • Stretching the twisted wire after done can improve on the quality of the final strand.
  • Short segments work best, as they do not entangle below.

title: Anti backlash lead screw example design

description.text:
This is a example how to make a anti-backlash lead screw using 2 nuts and this printed part.

The example shown uses 2 m5 nuts and a spring.

I have included the CAD file for you to examine in DesignSpark Mechanical.
Basically you will only slightly tighten the 2 nuts together so that the free play is taken out and then insert into the nut capture. Too tight and it will have a lot of friction.

This design has more drag than ball screws so you will need to use a light lubricant. Preferably containing teflon.

You will have to draw a new CAD file with the appropriate bolt holes for mounting and for your particular size threaded rod.
Print at 100%. I leave typically a 0.2mm clearance for the nut. so therefore, if you use a m6 threaded rod the nut is 10mm. I draw a 6 sided enclosure for the nut at 10.2mm

title: Extruder barrel cooling duct for MK5-6 v6

description.text: This is a derivative of my own prior extruder barrel cooling duct. ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8461 ) It is optimized for a 40mm fan, which won't fit inside the 35mm gap between the two large sides of a standard MK5-6 extruder. I find that PLA prints much better with active cooling directly on the barrel itself. The section STL is for a replacement side to the extruder. It is functionally identical to the original small acrylic piece that fits there - except that it has a big rectangular hole to allow additional ventilation. I've of course included the OpenSCAD design files, but I didn't try to make the fan mount terribly parametric. There are some variables you could set, like thickness to all parts, but it's not fully parametric. If you have a different fan from mine (40x40x26mm) then you're going to want to redesign the fan mount anyhow. The reason for the DXF of the front acrylic panel was so that I could essentially create a virtual extruder holder for making sure everything aligned. If you uncomment the section at the top, you can see it too. ;)

• Loosen bolts and remove front acrylic panel from the extruder holder.
  • Loosen bolts and remove the small left and right acrylic panels from the extruder holder.
  • Replace right side with large fan mount and cooling duct.
  • Replace left side with small hole-y side holder.
  • Replace front acrylic panel to the extruder holder.
  • Re-tighten all screws
  • Connect new fan, possibly with use of these sweet fan connectors http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8827
  • Print with PLA easier!

For now, file this one under "work-in-progress". Maybe someone can give me an idea of how to improve these?

description.text:
A few months ago, I read on rep-rap.org about a design for an extruder that used plastic pellets rather than filaments. An auger drove the pellets into the hot end. That auger was made using copper wire and some pipe, but I thought it would be a good idea to make a printable one... And then I forgot about it.
Recently, I was walking down Roncesvalles, which has been undergoing massive roadwork for about 2 years now. Across the street from my butcher was a machine for extruding road curbs in cement. At the part where the cement is fed into the machine, there was a large exposed auger... So I took a closer look, and it was in segments that were clearly bolted together. I thought: PRINTABLE!
Don't print this. I clearly have my ratios wrong. Bolt holes are not lined up. As usual, I've probably tried to make it too small too.

title: TBS Caipirinha Yi Action Cam Mount

description.text:
To scared to strap my GoPro 3+ to my TBS Caipirinha so I created this mount for the Xiaomi Yi Action Camera instead.
The mount is based on the design by Boonzie for the Hero2 camera.

Wrap a rubber band around the camera for a secure, jello reducing, fit in the case and further secure it with a velcro strap from flying out.

The lens cut out is large enough to allow you to mount a filter - e.g. TBS anti jello filter - to the camera.

2 versions of the mount are included:

  • standard version: camera only, slightly recessed, similar to the Hero3 mount from TBS
  • pocket version: camera + a pocket behind it for additional weight if necessary. The camera will be further forward this way and line up with the front of the wing. Weights can be added in the pocket behind the camera to balance the plane.

title: QAV250 AeroGuard - REMIXED with Lumenier logo

description.text:
I'm hoping that releasing this design does not upset anyone at Lumenier. I am not making money off of these and I doubt that they plan to release an aero-guard with the logo embedded in the side of it. If anyone from Lumenier sees this and would like me to take these down, please let me know and I will do so promptly.

This is a remix of this design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:617553, which was a remix of this design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:583027

There are 2 versions. One was thinned out in the middle to save weight. A set of these weighs around 16 grams. The other version is the original thickness and a set of these weighs around 21 grams.

I printed mine face down in PLA on blue painters tape. Try and use very wide tape or get the gaps between the tape extremely small and you will get a nice matte finish that looks good in contrast to the glossy carbon fiber..

One last note: when I first used 3D-printed aero guards without any holes in them, I had uncontrollable yaw issues. It was super twitchy and would whip around wildly with even mild yaw input. This same issue has occurred for some people when using the thin, flexible aero guard that Lumenier sells. (You will notice that they now have a disclaimer on their site stating that they are aware of the issue). Once I put the logos (holes) in these, the yaw issues that I was experiencing went away completely.
